      <h3 id="make"><a name=“make”><br></a></h3>
      <h3>How to make a Sour Dough Starter</h3>
      <strong>Let get us started: </strong><br>
      <p><strong>Some notes before we start:</strong><br> 
        <ul>
          <li>Please use only unbleached flour</li>
          <li>Please use only filtered water [no chlorine]</li>
          <li>Recommend to use a glass bowl to see progress. Lid is important</li>
        </ul>
       <br>
      </p>
     <p><strong>Important: </strong>Please do not get incouraged when you do not see much activity for a coulple of days. It will still work
        out. Also the water on the top of the sour dough starter is not a bad thing, it is called 'Hooch' and it is a collection of water created during 
        the process when the yeast has not enough 'food' anymore. Other microbioligy reaction taken over and creating the water.
        You can remove the liquid or stir it in. If the later, it might makes the dough a little bit more sour. I haven't tasted the difference
        yet but that might be just me. My suggestion is that you feed the dough more flour than the 1/2 cup but keep the amount of water. That will take 
        care of it.
      </p>
      <p class="scout-first-letter">When I am asking to increase the feeding schedule from daily to feed the starter every 12 hours, do not need to do it on the second means
        +/- 1 or 2 hours is fine as long the starter is not neglected for days.
      </p>
        <ol>
          <dt><strong>Day 1</strong></dt><dd>mix 1/2 cup of flour with 1/2 cup of water and set aside. Best with lid layed on top not closed.</dd>
          <dt><strong>Day 2</strong></dt><dd>just ventilate (open lid and let it breath for some minutes)</dd>
          <dt><strong>Day 3</strong></dt><dd>1. Remove half of the sour dough starter.</dd><dd>2. Feed the other half again with 1/2 cup of flour and 
            1/2 cup of water.</dd>
          <dt><strong>Day 4</strong></dt><dd>Note: Start feeding every 12 hours</dd><dd>1. Remove half of the sour dough starter.</dd><dd>2. Feed the other half again with 1/2 cup of flour and 
            1/2 cup of water.</dd>
          <dt><strong>Day 5</strong></dt><dd>Note: Start feeding every 12 hours</dd><dd>Dough might does not smell like yeast yet but that is normal</dd>
             <dd>1. Remove half of the sour dough starter.</dd><dd>2. Feed the other half again with 1/2 cup of flour and 
              1/2 cup of water.</dd>
          <dt><strong>Day 6</strong></dt><dd>Note: Start feeding every 12 hours</dd><dd>You should see some activity but no worries when
            not. Dough is active.</dd>
          <dd>1. Remove half of the sour dough starter.</dd><dd>2. Feed the other half again with 1/2 cup of flour and 
                1/2 cup of water.</dd>
          <dt><strong>Day 7</strong></dt><dd>Note: Start feeding every 12 hours</dd><dd>1. Remove half of the sour dough starter.</dd><dd>2. Feed the other half again with 1/2 cup of flour and 
                  1/2 cup of water.</dd> 
          <dt><strong>Day 8</strong></dt><dd>Note: One last feeding</dd><dd>Your Sour Dough Starter should be ready for baking or 
            to refrigerate it. If you have any concerns it is still too young and not strong enough keep feeding for 2 more days.</dd>            
        </ol>
